    tips:[
      "Japanese has three levels of politeness: 丁寧語 (polite), 尊敬語 (honorific/respectful), and 謙譲語 (humble).",
      "The same person will switch between formal and informal Japanese many times a day depending on context.",
      "When in doubt, err on the side of being more polite — it is considered less offensive than being too casual.",
      "にとって always takes the perspective of someone, followed by an evaluation: Xにとって、Y is (adjective).",
      "ため has two meanings (purpose vs. reason) — context and tense help distinguish them.",
      "Pay attention to sentence-ending particles like よ, ね, な, さ — they add nuance and mark speech style.",
    ],
